<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What a Soil Blocker Actually Does</h2>

  <p>
    A soil blocker compresses a moist soil mix into firm cubes that hold together without a container.
  </p>

  <p>
    These blocks:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>support seedlings without plastic trays</li>
    <li>encourage air pruning of roots</li>
    <li>allow easy transplanting</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The result is a more efficient and plant-focused system.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Soil Blocking Improves Root Growth</h2>

  <p>
    When roots reach the edge of a soil block, they’re exposed to air instead of circling a container. This naturally stops outward growth and encourages branching.
  </p>

  <p>
    This leads to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>denser root systems</li>
    <li>less transplant shock</li>
    <li>stronger plants overall</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It’s one of the biggest advantages of the method.
  </p>
</section>

